1. De-mean or Not


  • Theoretically, AR(\(p\)) has mean of 0. \[ X_t = X_{t-1} + e_t \hspace10mm e_t \sim WN(0,\sigma^2). \]

  • If the observed series looks like AR(\(p\)) with constant mean, our model is \[ Y_t = \mu + X_t, \hspace10mm \mbox{ where } \mu \mbox{ is a constant and $X_t$ is AR(p).} \]

  • That means, \(Y_t\) has a mean of \(\mu\), and we need to de-mean (de-trend) by letting \[ \hat X_t = Y_t - \bar Y. \] before modeling \(\hat X_t\) with zero-mean AR(\(p\)).

  • In ARMA modeling, it is common practice to just de-trend even when sample mean \(\bar Y\) is not significantly different from \(0\).

  • detrend=TRUE is default in ar().

  • If you use detrend=FALSE option, that means our model is \[ X_t = Y_t. \] and \(Y_t\) is believed to have mean of \(0\). \(Y_t\) is directly being modeled with zero-mean AR(p) model.

  • So if we let \[ Y2 = Y-mean(Y) \] Then use ar(Y2, demean=FALSE), then it is same as using demean=TRUE option.



Example: De-mean or not

  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5
  plot(Y, type="o")

  mean(Y)
## [1] 8.109229
  Fit3 <- ar(Y, aic=F, order.max=2)               # demean=TRUE is the default

2. Order Selection of AR(p)


    1. ACF and PACF
    1. AIC and log-likelihood
    1. Parameter Significance



a. ACF and PACF


  • ACF of AR(p) tails off
  • PACF of AR(P) cuts off at lag \(p\).
  • Theoretical value of PACF(\(h\)) are \(phi_h\).
  set.seed(345)     
  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5
  plot(Y, type="o")

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))  # two plots side by side
  acf(Y)                     # plot sample ACF of Y
  pacf(Y)                    # plot sample PACF of Y

  layout(1)                  # return to 1 plot layout



b. AIC


  • Likelihood function \[ L(\theta) = f(X_1) \, f(X_2) \, \cdots f(X_n) \]

  • Akaike Information Criteria: \[ \mbox{AIC} = -2 \, \log(\mbox{maximum likelihood}) + 2 k \] \(k=p+1\) if and \(k=p\) if .

  • Choose \(p\) that MINIMIZE AIC.

  • ar() chooses \(p\) value based on AIC automatically.



c. Parameter Significance


  • After \(p\) was suggested by AIC, test the pameter estimate for significance using large-sample 95% CI.

  • ar() uses Yule-Walker as default estimator.



Example: order selection

  set.seed(4772)                        # you don't need to do this  
  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 ) + 8.5     # simulate AR(2)

  #- 1. ACF and PACF
  layout(matrix(1:2, 1, 2))             # two plots side by side
  acf(Y)                                # plot sample ACF of Y
  pacf(Y)                               # plot sample PACF of Y

  layout(1)                             # return to 1 plot layout
  
  #- 2. AIC
  Fit8 <- ar(Y)                         # Fit AR(p). Find best p by AIC
  Fit8

Example: AIC Simulation Study

If we use AIC all the time, what is the probability we end up with correct \(p\)?

  • Set \(p=2\). Generate simulated AR(2).
  • Use ar(Y) and search for best \(p\) by using Minimum AIC.
  • Repeat 1000 times. How many time do we end up with right \(p\)?
  #- Simulation Study of choosing p by AIC
  Result <- 0
  for (i in 1:1000){
    Y <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 ) 
    Fit7 <- ar(Y)                         # find AR(p) by AIC
    # print(c(i, Fit7$order) )            # print order on screen (optional)
    Result[i] <- Fit7$order               # save value of p chosen
  }
  head(Result, 100)                       # first 100 p     
##   [1] 1 2 2 3 1 2 2 3 3 3 5 2 2 2 2 2 3 3 2 8 5 4 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 1 2 1 6
##  [36] 2 2 1 2 6 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 1 2 3 2 1 2 6 2 2 2 1 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 3 1 5 2
##  [71] 5 2 2 2 2 2 2 3 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 1 2 2 1 2 2 2 1 2 7 4 4 4 2
  mean(Result==2)                         # propotion of times p=2 
## [1] 0.636



3. Residual Analysis of AR(p)


  • After parameter estimation, say we have AR(2) model \[ X_t = \hat \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \hat \phi_2 X_{t-2} + e_t. \]

  • \(X_t\) are observations. We never get to observe \(e_t\).

  • We must estimate \(e_t\) by residuals.
    \[ \hat e_t = X_t -\hat \phi_1 X_{t-1} -\hat \phi_2 X_{t-2} \hspace10mm t= 3,4,\ldots,n \]

  • This is the reason, that for AR(\(p\)), first \(p\) residuals are NA.

  • If the model chosen is fitting the data adequately, \(\hat e_t\) should behave like \(e_t\). i.e. residuals should behave like White Noise.

  • Plot ACF and PACF of the residuals, and look for sign of non-WN.



Example: Residual Analysis

  Y <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 ) 
  Fit9 <- ar(Y, aic=F, order.max=2, demean=F)    # force p=2
  Fit9$ar
## [1] 0.5247036 0.3170003
  e.hat <- Fit9$resid                            # extract the residuals
  e.hat

Example: Dow Jones 1972

  # read in daily Dow Jones data from my website
  D  <- read.csv("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/pages/datasets/dowj.csv")  
  D1 <- ts(D, start=c(1,1), freq=1)   # turn the data into TS object
  plot(D1)

  Y <- diff(log(D1))                  # Take log-difference 
  plot(Y, type='o')

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1,2))            # 2 plots side by side
  acf(Y)
  pacf(Y)

  layout(1)                           # reset the layout 
    
  Fit11 <- ar(Y)      # Fit AR(p) default use Y-W for estimator, 
                      # and AIC to look for best p. demean=TRUE is also default
  Fit12 <- ar(Y, aic=TRUE,  order.max=20)    # best p is chosen by aic (same as above)
  
  Fit11                                      # see the summary of fit
## 
## Call:
## ar(x = Y)
## 
## Coefficients:
##      1  
## 0.4274  
## 
## Order selected 1  sigma^2 estimated as  1.098e-05
  sqrt( Fit11$asy.var.coef )                 # SE of the estimator 
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.1043933
  Fit13 <- ar(Y, aic=FALSE,  order.max=2)    # force fit AR(2)
  Fit13
## 
## Call:
## ar(x = Y, aic = FALSE, order.max = 2)
## 
## Coefficients:
##      1       2  
## 0.3808  0.1091  
## 
## Order selected 2  sigma^2 estimated as  1.099e-05
  sqrt( Fit13$asy.var.coef )                 # SE of the estimator 
## Warning in sqrt(Fit13$asy.var.coef): NaNs produced
##           [,1]      [,2]
## [1,] 0.1155538       NaN
## [2,]       NaN 0.1155538
  e.hat <- Fit11$resid                       # extract residuals from the 1st fit 
  plot(e.hat, type="o")                      # plot residuals

  layout(matrix(1:2, 1,2))                   # 2 plots side by side
  acf(e.hat, na.action=na.pass)              # check for autocorrelation in residuals
  pacf(e.hat, na.action=na.pass)

  layout(1)                                  # reset the layout


Summary


  • To fit AR(p), you must first decide to de-mean or not. Its customary to just de-mean.
    ar() does that by default.

  • Look at sample ACF and sample PACF to guess p.

  • Akaike Information Criteria can also be used to look for the best \(p\). ar() function does that automatically by default. You want MINIMUM AIC.

  • Check parameter significance of estimated parameters. If the last parameter is not significant, reduce \(p\) by 1, and fit again.

  • After getting the suggested best \(p\) from AIC, fit model with p+1, and see if the last parameter estimate comes out non-significant.

  • Check residuals for autocorrelation by plotting reiduals and plotting ACF and PACF.

  Y    <- arima.sim(list(ar = c(.6, .3) ), 100 )  + 8.5

  Fit6

# Example: Dow Jones 1972

  # read in daily Dow Jones data from my website
  D  <- read.csv("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/pages/datasets/dowj.csv")  
  D1 <- ts(D, start=c(1,1), freq=1)   # turn the data into TS object
  plot(D1)
  
  Y <- diff(log(D1))                  # Take log-difference 
  plot(Y, type='o')
  layout(matrix(1:2, 1,2))            # 2 plots side by side
  acf(Y)
  pacf(Y)
  layout(1)                           # reset the layout 
    
  Fit11 <- ar(Y)      # Fit AR(p) default use Y-W for estimator, 
                      # and AIC to look for best p. demean=TRUE is also default
  Fit12 <- ar(Y, aic=TRUE,  order.max=20)    # best p is chosen by aic (same as above)
  
  Fit11                                      # see the summary of fit
  sqrt( Fit11$asy.var.coef )                 # SE of the estimator 

  
  Fit13 <- ar(Y, aic=FALSE,  order.max=2)    # force fit AR(2)
  Fit13
  sqrt( Fit13$asy.var.coef )                 # SE of the estimator 

  e.hat <- Fit11$resid                       # extract residuals from the 1st fit 
  plot(e.hat, type="o")                      # plot residuals
  layout(matrix(1:2, 1,2))                   # 2 plots side by side
  acf(e.hat, na.action=na.pass)              # check for autocorrelation in residuals
  pacf(e.hat, na.action=na.pass)
  layout(1)                                  # reset the layout
